-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Show that the sum S = 2010 + 2011 + … + 4018 is divisible by 2009. 2. [Key Idea] Either count the 2009 equally-spaced terms directly or reduce each term modulo 2009; both routes reveal an unavoidable factor 2009. 3. [Proof] Method 1 (arithmetic-progression formula) • Number of terms: n = 4018 – 2010 + 1 = 2009. • Average of first and last terms: (2010 + 4018)/2 = 6028/2 = 3014. • Hence S = n · (average) = 2009 · 3014, so 2009 | S. Method 2 (pairwise residues) • Reduce each addend modulo 2009: 2010 ≡ 1, 2011 ≡ 2, … , 4017 ≡ 2008, 4018 ≡ 0 (mod 2009). • Thus S ≡ 1 + 2 + … + 2008 + 0. • Sum 1 + … + 2008 = 2008·2009/2, which has the factor 2009. • Therefore S ≡ 0 (mod 2009). 4. [Conclusion] In either view the sum S is a multiple of 2009, so its residue modulo 2009 is 0.
